\section{Introduction}
Socrates and Plato were both ancient Greek philosophers who greatly influenced Western philosophy. Although Socrates did not leave any written works, his teachings have been preserved through the writings of his students, particularly Plato.

\section{Socratic Theory}

\subsection{Socratic Method}
Socrates is best known for his Socratic Method, a form of philosophical inquiry which involves asking questions to stimulate critical thinking and to expose the contradictions in a person's beliefs. This method is based on the idea that true knowledge can only be obtained through dialogue and self-examination.

\subsection{Ethical Focus}
Socrates placed a strong emphasis on ethics and morality. He believed that the ultimate goal of philosophy is to lead a virtuous life. He also maintained that "virtue is knowledge," suggesting that moral wrongdoing stems from ignorance.

\subsection{The Unexamined Life}
Socrates famously stated that "the unexamined life is not worth living." This reflects his belief in the importance of self-reflection and critical thinking as a means to achieve wisdom and understanding.

\section{Platonic Theory}

\subsection{Theory of Forms}
Plato's most well-known philosophical theory is the Theory of Forms. According to this theory, the physical world we experience is a mere imitation of a higher, more perfect realm of abstract forms or ideas. These forms are eternal, unchanging, and exist independently of our perceptions.

\subsection{The Allegory of the Cave}
To illustrate the Theory of Forms, Plato presented the Allegory of the Cave, a story in which prisoners are chained in a cave and can only see shadows of objects projected onto the wall. When one prisoner is freed and sees the true forms of things outside the cave, he comes to understand the limitations of his previous beliefs.

\subsection{The Divided Line and the Theory of Knowledge}
Plato also introduced the Divided Line, a model that divides reality into two realms: the sensible world (perceptible objects) and the intelligible world (forms or ideas). He believed that knowledge is gained through the process of recollection, where the soul remembers the forms it encountered before birth.

\section{Conclusion}
In conclusion, while both Socrates and Plato focused on the pursuit of knowledge and virtue, their philosophical theories differ significantly. Socrates emphasized the importance of self-examination and dialogue in the pursuit of wisdom, while Plato introduced the concept of forms and the idea that knowledge is gained through recollection of the true, perfect realm.

\end{document}
